column17: The MCPN North Aurora clinic is the biggest and busiest clinic in the system.  It requires a significant more attention and upkeep than the rest of the sites regarding the ROR program. I am currently working with the two designated HealthCorps members on creating a system to track books, ensure distribution, and keep stocked.

column16: Program lapse due to ADMINISTRATIVE personnel changes
column17: Monica and Emily, ROR coordinators, have made huge strides in promoting, tracking, and educating the MCPN clinic and staff about the ROR program.  During a site visit, Ann Valdez-PA at North Aurora indicated that most of the providers are familiar with the program but often times do not remember to take out the tracking slip and or it has already fallen out of the book.  This commentary indicates that the program is being carried out at MCPN correctly and books are getting into the hands of patients, however, the tracking system is not accurately reflecting the programs success. That said, provider turnover and staffing continues to be an issue effecting the ROR program.
MCPN clinics experienced a decline in well child visits during the last reporting period. MCPN continues to explore explanations for the drop in well child visits.

column17: With the changing economy, our patient load is down - people are apparently skipping well visits

Our numbers have been dropping each 6-month report.  In that period the clinic has moved, the recession has encouraged many to skip well visits, and there has been some loss in medical personnel hours.  They are mostly part-time volunteer doctors.

Multiple staff changes and hours available have resulted in fewer child visits and also, we believe, in the accuracy of reporting.  Because we have no electronic medical records, and the clinic tracks a wider age range than we do for ROR, we are changing how we estimate our visit numbers.  In the past we extrapolated from a trusted staff estimate of percentages (and our core staff was on-board 100%).  Now we are trying to estimate from clinic numbers, based on how often children are brought in at different ages.  For example the clinic tracks 4 days, 2 weeks, 1 month, 2 months which presumably always come in.  Staff says few come in for visits with no shots, etc. etc.  We as reporters are having to adjust.

We have new pediatric medical assistant but more importantly we have a new electronic medical record that started in September, which was time consuming and distracting to regular appointment procedure,  so our numbers may seem different than before.  We can now very accurately record well child visits and our EMR does not have a book distribution field yet

our number of children coming to ICHC has gone down due to new birth control distribution and extreme competition for peds patients through out the city.
this is the first time we have been able to use our Electronic records to gather well child visits.

We have only begun to use our electronic records to gather well child visit numbers. I am still not convinced it is gathering the data correctly. As the books are counted as they are set out on the shelf for the MA to distribute.

Dr. Cooley does the majority of the well child visits.  She was on maternity leave for 3 months.  . We have new pediatric templates in a new EMR since1 10 2018. I just discovered that the pediatric well child visits no longer have a reminder to give the ROR books.  So I suspect that volunteers and staff who infrequently give well child visits did not distribute books.

column17:
Three things:
One: we did have a lapse of books (books ordered, delivered to the wrong location within the hospital, eventually found)

Two: National ROR delivered 12 boxes of the same book to us which did not help our supplies

Three: we are still perfecting the collection of electronic medical record data on how many books are distributed. I believe with each report this is becoming more accurate.

We are actually doing very well at giving out books, but we are still having difficulties tracking how many exactly were given out. We are still workig on that with our electronic medical record. I have consulted with them and they say one of the issues is educating residents on the use of the smart text cues.

We are working on improving the quality of documentation of books distributed.  We will be reviewing charts to determine which providers are not using the data-gathering ROR question within the electronic medical record.  As the new director for ROR at our site, I am commmitted to improving our documentation and distribution.

We have spent a great deal of time with our electronic medical record technical support personnel to investigate data collection for our ROR program.  At this time, we are gathering much more accurate data through our medical record system, as confirmed by manual chart review.  We will continue to work to improve the distribution rate, but are pleased that our numbers are much improved due to the efforts of our medical record support people.
We are continuing to work on the accuracy of our Electronic Medical Record for reporting books given.  It is not picking up all charts in which "book given and discussed" was marked.

We are continuting to work on figuring out best method to track books.

We are moving to a new clinic next month and will be divided into 4 "pods" - each functioning like a separate clinic.  We will be trialing best locations for books (likely within each pod).

I will likely be getting a new shipping address for BOOKS (paper mail will still go to the same address) - I will let you know as soon as I know!

We have actually had a large INCREASE in the number of well child visits - and thus number of books distributed - in the last 6 months.  Our clinic moved out of the hospital and into the neighboring building.  We have more space and are able to accommodate more appoinment slots.  

As a result, we ran out of books and money for our clinic for the first time ever this month.

column17: Our clinic moved locations this fall.  The clinic was closed for almost 2 weeks and following the move providers had only partial schedules filled for a number of weeks with the expectation that there would be glitches in the new building and late missed visits for patients with the new location.

We switched to a new note-writing functionality within the EMR that changed the way the data is captured.  The numbers are a little low, likely due to the place where the provider must enter the data, and we will be working on improving the data capture within the new system!  

Also note that I do not have data for the 0-5 month visits

Supply Chain issues - our book orders from AAB have been slow to arrive and are often just partial fulfillment.  AAB has communicated that there have been issues getting books to their warehouse to then get out to clinics.  We still have a partial order pending from November.  As such, we have had gaps with no books.

The "supply chain" issues and delayed shipping of books have been a challenge.  Without knowing how delayed the order will be, it is hard to predict when the order should be placed.  We do not have unlimited storage for our books, so we have to take that into account.  We have had some months where we are out of books for particular age groups.

column17: We started a new tracking system which requires providers to click a box in EMR. This may not  accurately reflect the amount of books given out due to them not remembering to click the box.

We are working on tightening our processes for data collection and reporting. It has been a work in progress to be able to accurately collect data and report it in a way that is representative of the work that we are doing. We implemented a way of tracking how many books we are giving out through our EMR, but it has taken some trial and errors to decipher the most accurate ways of pulling the data from this tracking mechanism. The numbers we are reporting are lower than they have been historically. We attribute this to more accurate reporting abilities, being low on providers at times in different clinics, and the time of year. The reporting time is when we see an influx of sick visits and therefore, we utilize our appointments for sick patients rather than WCC.

Data collection indicated that the number of books given in all sites other than our Thornton clinic exceeded the number of wellchecks during the period-the total number of books for those sites were adjusted down.

column16: New program is not yet fully operational
column17: We haven't been giving out books in Lakewood for the full 6 month period yet, I also projected the number of WCC as it is expected to be the same as the Denver clinic but I don't know an accurate number yet for Lakewood.

Clarification regarding total numbers:

We use a "dummy" billing code to indicate when a ROR book is given at a WCC and unfortunately new staff in the billing department unaware of this process removed the codes for several patients. We have corrected this and know for sure that the numbers of books given in Thornton and Aurora should be close to 100% at each site, however we need to present what the data is currently indicating.

Race Ethnicity:

Also, with regard to race and ethnicity in the category of Hispanic and Latino our numbers were 48%, however because many of our families self-identify as both Hispanic Latino as well as white black unknown or other, etc.,. numbers appear in more than one category making the total number exceed 100% and because we cant submit the report with this category exceeding 100% the Hispanic Latino info was removed.

Race Ethnicity:

column17: We are unable to separate well child checks by age groups. There for this well child check number includes other age groups that are not receiving books.

1) Our clinic moved from an old building to a brand new facility over a few weeks in December. During the packing, moving, and unpacking processes, the ROR program was less available than usual. Now that we are in our new facility, however, it is up and running and working very well!

2) We cannot screen out kids under 6 months and over 5 years from our overall total of well-child checks.

3) Our site coordinators are AmeriCorps members, and the position changes every year. There is a 6-week gap in between the end of one member's term and the beginning of the next. For this 6 weeks, the clinic does its best to continue the ROR program, but because they are so busy with the amount of patients we see, sometimes the months of August and September are slow in terms of book give outs because of the lack of a site coordinator.

column17: We had a number of clinical personnel changes, the former co-ordinator moved to another site within the clinic, and she had only been in place for 1 progress cycle. column17: We have been having some very difficult months at Salud. I took over the program just before our last status report in March 2019, and since then scheduling changes have required me to see a huge increase in patients. I haven't been able to keep up with ordering. An additional issue is that it has been hard to track our balance, our listed balance on the website is $0, I received a number of different invoices from Scholastic and we've had difficulty sorting them out, even with RoR help.

We are working to consistently improve the RoR program. This is the first reporting period since I took over RoR at Salud Commerce City that we have dependable numbers from our electronic health records thanks to expanded help from my administrative staff, and I was able to confirm the number by checking back in our raw data. The next phase of improvement is the direct tracking of books, rather then using the ordering records and inventory count that I used for the number above, in the 1 2020 - 6 2020 period I will start implementing and refining a receipt system, where we collect a receipt from each book distributed. I will be rolling this out this month (March 2020). Also, we have held 2 RoR trainings in the last 3 months, and we are working to improve our literacy-rich environment. I expect better numbers next period and throughout 2020.
Weve been working to improve and have improved since last period. Were hoping to do even better next period.
We started counting our book distribution in May, 2021. Between 5 2021-7 2021 we distributed 275 books.

Rifle began distributing books as of July 1st.  Based on the numbers of books given out in July and August, I estimate around 20 well-child checks per month, so we will need around 120 books for the six month period.

Basalt began distributing books on August 1st and I am estimating they will need around 15 books per month, so 90 books for the six month period.

column17: I wish I could explain the steep decline in the consistency of our ROR book distributions. It seems that training retraining needs to occur more frequently.

Covid 19 has put a toll on the number of Pt we see in the clinic.  The number of children allowed in the clinic suffer because we are not seeing anyone in clinic with symptoms; cough, congestion, fever, runny nose, and headache.  As many know children almost always have at least one of these going on.  When Pt has symptoms the well child check apt turns in to a sick visit and the child's annual gets pushed out further.

I believe this was during a transition period when we were changing site coordinators and we were also out of money.  COVID has also created some hurdles we have not been able to overcome.  Pt are not allowed in the clinic with symptoms and most children 0 to 5 have a constant runny nose and post nasal drip cough.  Pt are being evaluated in the ambulance bay for symptoms but our providers do not feel they can do an adequate evaluated for a well child check in the ambulance bay.

Our billing department is a few months behind and they could only track the Well Child Checks that have been entered.  We also have a Nurse Practitioner that sees a lot of kids and if they come in for something else and he sees that they need a Well Child Check he goes ahead and does the WCC.  So that may contribute to some of the discrepancy in the numbers too.

column17: During this 6 month time period, we began to implement our electronic health record.  During this time we have had significantly reduced the number of appointments available so that providers could begin to become proficient in their use of the EHR.

We have been in the process of implementing our electronic health record which has resulted in a reduced number of clinic visits.  In addition, we are also short 2 full time physician assistants and therefore our number of available clinic visits has been significantly reduced during this time period.

The number of well child checks conducted by our clinic continues to remain much lower than in the past and this is due to a decreased number of overall patient visits due to implementation of our electronic medical record.  We had hoped to increase visit numbers back up to pre-implementation numbers, but this has not yet been possible.  We also recently hired 2 new midlevel providers and their transition may be responsible for the decreased percentage of well child visits covered.

We are currently undergoing many workflow changes providing increased levels of responsibilities to our MA who are the individuals responsible for getting books to the providers.  We will hopefully be able to get back to our high level of distribution as these workflows become a more automatic part of their practice.

column17: I am uncertain about Yuma County and why there is a large discrepancy.  However, for our Phillips County site, our primary immunization and community health nurse was on maternity leave for March, April and May.  We had numerous nurses travel in to cover her clinics during those three months.  It is very possible that with that site not being thier familiar, primary site and thier routine being broken up a bit that the books were not distributed as usual.

I am uncertain why there continues to be a discrepancy at the Yuma office. There has been a change of nursing staff in the Morgan office that could explain the lower numbers. Nurses from other offices traveled to Fort Morgan to help provide services until new nurses could be hired and trained. It could be that they were out of their normal routine and did not remember to distribute books like they normally do. Once one nurse was hired, she often did the work that is normally shared by two. It could be that she felt like she did not have time to provide anticipatory guidance and a book to each child.

The beginning of 2013 marked a change in the immunization program. Due to a change at the federal level, starting January 1, 2013, the publically funded vaccines through the Vaccines for Children (VFC) and Section 317 programs are no longer authorized for use in children with private insurance or CHP+.  This means that the number of children served through Northeast Colorado Health Departments immunization program has decreased. During this reporting time, we have increased children served at Healthy Child clinics and Child Finds resulting in an overall somewhat lower number than in the past.

The past year has marked a reduced number of children served by the immunization program because of new guidelines for the use of federally funded vaccine. We anticipate that the current numbers will continue to be our average.

Due to COVID we had stopped doing many of our clinics in person and used tele-health services to support our clients.  Toward the end we were able to start having in person clinics where we provided Reach Out and Read books to children ages birth to 5 years of age.   These clinics included CU Health Children's Hospital and Healthy Child Clinics.

column17: We usually see more kids in the July-Dec part of the year.  Our Health Dept had to terminate our WCC but we are working on reaching more children in different areas which may replace this.
We may be increasing our book distribution due to several MD offices here in our county not giving children's immunizations at this time.  But we do have some books on hand for this increase.

The # of children seen and books given will most likely increase this year because one of our very busy practices in town with a Pediatrician is no longer giving any imms and we will be picking up the slack.
In our entire county we and one medical provider are the ONLY ones giving immunizations.  Our rates have climbed monthly due to this.

It is very hard to get an accurate prediction - I think this is close. Due to the affordable care act we now charge for immunization and this may be affecting our numbers. At this time we are one of two providers doing immunizations, but this is due to change in the coming year.

column17: We received some free books through a different program and where appropriate (due to the subject matter of the book, ie nutrition) we gave those out instead of ROR books. This may account for our difference in numbers.

WIC does not always hand out books when they recertify children. 
I'm not sure why they don't. It is just their policy.

We purchased 551 books with the Scholastic funds. 
We have 1084 books at both sites, which account for "Bonus" and "Sustainable" books plus the books we purchased with our grant money.

The number of well child examines have fallen through out the summer and early fall. 
Loss of income have caused parents not to bring in their children for vaccinations.
WIC changed it's computer programing and they were out a week to train. After returning,they did not schedule as many clients as usual, in order to familiarize themselves with the new program.
Our census has been down the last 6 months.
We have not seen as many well child visits as we usually do.
Vaccinations are down.

Dollars and or in-kind donations awarded by your Coalition 2093 is incorrect. We received no grants this year. The only money that we received was from ROR.
I could not delete that amount. It is incorrect.
B. Kelly

Pulled all Bonus books of shelf and added them to ?Gently used.
Originally, I did not know that Bonus books need not be counted.

I think it would be helpful to have another staff-wide training.  Day to day it doesn't seem like we're forgetting to give books to almost 1 2 our well-child visits, but we have had a lot of staff turnover in the last 6-12 months.
We're still working on getting everyone to give out books at EVERY well-child visit.

Ok, I'm not sure what happened that we supposedly gave out more books than we had WCCs.  And I definitely don't see how our numnber of well-child exams dropped to almost 25% of previous 6 mos.  I'm going to have them re-run the repost, but it probably won't be back in time for the report deadline.  This is frustrating...

Administration has yet to get me the report on our actual number of well visits for July-Dec 2010.  I understand our administration has been in touch with ROR and we were to use last report's info as a temporary measure.  I'm really sorry.

We're trying!  I'm not sure if it may be a problem with the slips we use to keep track of the ROR books given out or if it's just the volume of books we give out or if our record extraction from our EHR is overcounting the number of WCCs we see.

As of January 2012 we were still waiting for our bulk book order from Scholastic for the January-June 2011 reporting period.  We were most recently told that the order had been received but for some reason was never shipped by the warehouse.  Therefore, we had only minimal books to give for about 2 1 2 months.

We currently have received that bulk book order and are fairly well stocked for books for ages 2+.  However, we have < 30 books appropriate for ages 18 mos and younger.
We did have a couple of months in early 2012 when we did not have sufficient books to give.

I'm not sure how we went over!  I do know that we changed our computer software in I believe it was October, and I believe there are some problems with getting charts submitted for last fall, maybe due to the change.  I think the reports on the number of well child visits are drawn from the billing.  It may be that there were more well child checks that this number reflects.

We had about 4 weeks with no books in some of the age   language subsets.  It always seems like our data for the report comes in so late that we don't get to receive books for that time period until late in the cycle.  We're working harder on getting grants   donated books.

Also, our numbers of WCCs are significantly higher this reporting period than previously.  In fact, originally our IT department's report showed us has haveing seen 4600 well child visits for the time period.  They re-ran the numbers, and they are significantly improved, but I need to clarify the way they get the numbers.  We were always consistently at about 3000 for the prior several reports.
April and May were pretty slow months for us.  We have had a great turnover of stoff over the last several months and that may have played a role.  It seems to be picking up again.
We are working on a better system for tracking purposes, and also training because of staff turnover. There was a lack of inventory for weeks that also was a cause of staff changes.

column17: Rose Family Medicine Residency is in the process of hiring another Medical Assistant (MA) which may assist with the efficiency of the program.  At RFMR the MA's are responsible for book dispersement to the Medical Doctors.

I would also like to add that although it states we have 26 physicians giving books- we are a residency, therefore we only have 4-7 physicians per day seeing patients. 
We are also going to be implementing an Electronic Health Record System at RFMR (June 2010), which will assist with more accurate data with the number of Well Child Visits.

We are please with this outcome as we were fully staffed and came close to our Well Child Visits number to the Total Books Distributed.  We are in the process of scheduling our Site Observation with Reach Out and Read staff to train our new Resident Intern class.

We are more on target this year than any other year in participating with the ROR Program. MA's are proactive and distribute on a consistent basis. We hope to increase our WCC in the future as our program continues to grow in turn reflecting an increase in our book distribution.

RFMR recently implemented ECW (electronic health record system) which has tremendously decreased our patient numbers. We had to decrease patient numbers by 3 4 in the beginning months of implementation hence the drastic decrease of WCC from last year. We are pleased with the distribution of our Reach Out and Read books to our patients. We have had some staff turn-over with residents graduating, new intern class, and a new Medical Assistant joining our program.
We are pleased with our outcome!

In the past we have selected appropriate books for our clinic (provided our patients with more of a selection, not as big of a need for books in Spanish). We found it useful to select the books that were appropriate for our clinic. We are currently still in the process of implementing ECW (Electronic Health Record) and are in the process of hiring for more MA's and faculty MD's as we recently experienced turnover. However, the program is one that we hope to keep in existence as more and more physicians graduate and bring ROR to other clinics.

We experienced an extremely difficult past year as we implemented ECW Electronic Health record at RFMR. This process unfortunatley placed a lot of our programs on hold until it became a stable system at our clinic. Patient numbers decreased as visit times increased, documentation was not efficient, and our physicans to patiient visit was cut by 3 4 until the system became effective for visits and documentation purposes.

We have finally established a program to run WCC through our ECW system and we are continuously creating teams to improve RFMR's functionality (ie; PCMH). We recently lost our program operator and executive director, we are looking to hire another full-time MA as we are understaffed. I will begin doing more refresher trainings with the staff and physicians to ensure that ROR remains a valuable asset of RFMR. (I am also waiting for the new vender "All About Books" to become primary vender as I find their program meets our needs more than previous venders have.

We recently moved books to a new area where the PCP's will be distributing books to the children. The PCP's felt this new process is more "hands on" and allows them to complete the early intervention screenings.
This is most likely the closest we have been in a while to the WCC and books distributed thanks to ACA and allowing more new patients to be added to our schedules.

The month of August was very busy with our well child visits but were unable to  distribute any books that month due to low staffing and the ability to re-order more books.

column17:
The Nurse Family Partnership program became fully operational in April, so their numbers do not reflect a typical visiting pattern.

The Mesa County Health Department (Immunizations) always more than doubles the number of well child visits they have in the month of August.  So their numbers are a little low as well.

Mesa County Health Department has been restructured in the past 6 months. The Nurse Family Partnership has undergone staffing changes and has been with out 2 RN'S for several months.  We look forward to being fully staffed this year and having the ability to give out more books.

Our clinic has seen high turn over in personell. Also, we have had nurses out on FMLA so our client caseloads have gone down. However, as of this month we are currently fully staffed and are increasing client caseloads.

Both NFP and the Health Clinics have had turn over in this 6 month period. As new personnel is hired within NFP they must work up to full casload and therefore our distibution numbers do not accuratley reflect our typical distibution. The health clininc has also experienced turn over and as they hire new personnel, they must also be trained before working independently and then at that point they can give out books on their own.

Nurse Family Partnership has two new staff members.  Both nurses' are currently building their caseloads and one has recently completed training.  When a client enters our program in NFP she is pregnant, therfore, it will be awhile before our clients infant reach the age at which we handout books.  Since our last report, we have implamented a different tracking method for ROR,therefore, our numbers above indicate change.

Since the last ROR report was submitted the tracking of books given out by Nurse Family Partnership has been refined, therefore our number of well child visits indicate change.  Our site continues to experience staffing changes, but as listed above we are distributing more books then previously noted.

The NFP site in Mesa County has had changes within personnel.  Within the last 6 months we have hired 6 new staff members. We have a scheduled training for ROR October 2, 2013.  Our site continues to refine our process of distributing books at the recommended time.

Several reasons are for this; our clinic had been closed for a time period during which it was remodeled. During that time frame the Administrator changed hands. In the NFP program we had nurses building their caseload during this time frame. They will have babies beginning summer of 2015.

The caseload in NFP is low right now due to clients graduating from the program and clients moving out-of-county. Recent personnel changes during this progress report contributes to the lower well child visits for NFP. 
As for the clinic at MCPH, there is one full time nurse that is giving out ROR books which impacts the number of books being distributed during this time frame.

In the past six months, 4 new staff members have started within the NFP team.  Thus, we are not at full client caseload capacity.  A new nurse in NFP has nine months to build up her caseload.   

In the clinic the full time staff member went to PRN.  The full time position will be filled within the month.

In addition to our Well Child visits, we had a "Book Party"!  The Book Party Children's Health Fair had representatives from all the children's services on the Towaoc Reservation including the Registered Dietician, Food Commodities, Library, Immunizations RN, Head Start, Recreation Center, WIC, Public Health Nurses and others.  We had reading information, health information, sign-up options and community service information.  The event was attended by 51 children who received Reach Out and Read Books via the nurses and doctors that serve our clinic.  Parents attended with their children and Head Start teachers were very helpful in making the event a huge success.  The community was delighted about the Reach Out and Read involvement in this Native American setting and featured the event on their local TV and newspaper.

column17: Our program completes an ASQ with clients at 2 month intervals, which is more frequent than scheduled well child visits.  Our program has made it a priority to give each child a book at every ASQ, which means the child receives a new book every 2 months.  We also give away the gently used books that are donated to our program.  Used books are given during the months that a child does not have an ASQ and get a new book.  This is why our total books distributed is higher than our well child visits.

During the time frame of this reporting period, our program has seen a slight decrease in the number of clients served.  This has resulted in a slight decrease in the total number of books distributed.  We provide a book to the families each time we complete an ASQ on the child, which is every two months.  Since ASQ are not completed until the child is born, our pregnant clients do not receive reach out and read books.  This also affects our total books distributed if our program is currently serving more pregnant women during the reporting period.

Our NFP site is approved to serve 65 families.  Due to COVID and the resulting difficulty in enrolling families into the program, our site is currently only serving 50 clients.  However, due to a return of in-person visits, the number of families served and reach out and read books distributed has increased since the last progress report.

Our NFP site is approved to serve 65 families.  However, currently our program is serving 54 families, which is increased from 50 families reported on in our last progress report.  Our site continues to strategize in order to recover from the challenges that COVID presented in enrolling clients into the NFP program.

Our NFP site is approved to serve 65 families.  However over the last 6 months, our site only served 56 families, which is an increase of 2 families since the last ROR report.  Our site continues to strategize in order to recover from the challenges that COVID presented for in-home visitation programs such as Nurse Family Partnership.

column17: We are now fully funded. We are also short on Providers at this time.  Maternity leaves and leaves of absence.  Not sure when that will be back to normal.  It was definitely a slow half of the year.

column17: The report reflects date from 02 10 2017 through 7 14 17.  This Spring we changed our tracking process and have also changed the site administrator in those months so this time frame is what most accurately reflects the data we have collected.  There is a slight discrepancy in that the count for the books we gave out was a few more than the number of Well Child Visits done.  This may be due to different tracking in our 2 offices, some books may have been counted twice, I have no way to determine this.

I'm not sure why we have a record of distributing more books than we had number of well child visits.  I wonder if some of the visits for 6-12 months were not coded correctly as they are not "annual" visits but I think we are giving out a book each time for 6 months 8 months, possibly 10 months and then 12 months.

We are also still figuring out the ratio of Spanish and English.  Currently the majority of the books we have left are in Spanish (some are over a year old) and we are nearly out of English books in our main office.
This report is through 6 12 18

The report that we run from our EMR to get this data has been updated to reflect more accurate data, so this report will look different from our previous report.  Some of our well child checks were not counted in our previous report because the CPT codes were billed with modifiers.  Those visits are now included to obtain more accurate data.  Since there is a change in our data it is hard to determine if we have declined in the percentage of books we hand out or if our old report was off.

Unsure if we are missing the bookmarks from some books we gave out, seems we have gone through more books than this.  When I look at our numbers for the past month (July 2019) We had 30 well child checks and gave out 24 books (80%).  We will look at adjusting our tracking process.  I do think our average is a bit higher than reflected in the report.

column16: Program lapse due to CLINICAL personnel changes

column17: The start date at our clinic was 8 19 13. From 8 19 13 to 12 31 13, we handed out a book attempted to give a book 100% of the time.

Significant MA turnover, including 5-7 new hires, that has been illustrated in our ROR workflow that requires MAs to remember to handout the paperwork and book. Based on the increasing discrepancy in WCC and book handout, we will do a reminder informational session with our staff.

Our clinic has hired approximately 20 new MAs in the past two years and has experienced rapid turnover. Additionally, in the past year we have implemented a new clinic workflow model and have spent substantial hours training MAs on their new job. Therefore, it has been difficult to find effective and meaningful methods, given the clinic chaos if you will, to implement procedures in which the MAs do not forget to provide patients with books at their appointments. However, we hope to slowly discuss this more over the next 6 mo- one year in ways that will not overwhelm our staff and find methods that ensure we are not missing opportunities to hand out books.

column16: Program lapse due to CLINICAL personnel changes
column17: As you may know (and can see from our numbers expanding year after year), our clinic numbers have grown substantially and we have almost doubled our MA staff with significant turnover. It appears in the past 6 months, we have maintained the number of books we are handing out however this is not kept up with our rapid clinical growth.

Of note, we are collecting more of our data (ethnicity race, language spoken, insurance) via our EMR instead of patient self-report. This may change how our demographics appear in this report given some EMR data constraints. Unfortunately, we still only know the # of books distributed based on paper sheets turned in by the MAs.

column17: We have added new providers to our practice. We have also moved to a new building in Feb. 2019 and was not able to distribute books accordingly.

Due to COVID-19, we have seen a decrease in how many well visits were seen at our Wheat Ridge location. Our Wheat Ridge location began seeing all sick visits towards the beginning of March, while we saw all our well visits at our Thornton location. The well visits definitely had an increase in our Thornton office where we would see up to 60 patients a day. This really helped with the Reach Out and Read program because we started giving out more books. We predict that our Thornton location will continue to see only well visits until September, and our Wheat Ridge location began seeing well visits again beginning July.

COVID has affected our clinic in different ways. At our Thornton location we have never stopped seeing well checks, our numbers have been pretty much the same. Our Wheat Ridge location started seeing well checks a few months into the COVID pandemic and their numbers have increased as well. Because of the pandemic, we also have hundreds of patients under the age of 5 who have not been seen for their well checks in over a year, and this affects our normal number of well checks in a 6 month period as well. We are doing our best to fit in as many patients as we can to get caught up with their well checks and this makes us go through our Reach Out and Read books very quickly leaving us empty at times.

column17: We had some difficulty with ordering enough books for each age group, so were out of a specific age group when needed.  I believe we have resolved that issue.

The number is likely under reported as we have been tracking the book distribution by placing a colored index card in each book and removing the card when the book is given.  We then count the number of index cards at the end of each month.  I believe at times, the card gets lost or does not get removed before the book is given, thus under reporting how many we are giving.
We have begun a new process of counting our books at the beginning of the week and the end of the week and matching that number to the number of index cards we have collected.  When we get a new order of books, we add them at the beginning of the week so our total adds up.
Our number is overstated because we included books that were given to 0-5 month old and we did not count separately.

Our staffing was impacted and the MA's who usually keep track of books distributed were not consistently in the office.  I am confident that all children received a book, but our tracking of it was impacted by staffing issues.

There is about 5% discrepancy due to being new to the program. Staff at some clinics were still getting in the habit of distributing books during wellness visits and might have forgotten at times. Some clinics did not begin distributing books until a week or two into the program due to clinic champions still getting trained. 
Did not expand to Wheatridge, Rock Creek and Arapahoe clinics until January 2018.

There were about 1921 less books distributed to the total well-child visits. The discrepancy is due to couple factors:
1. 3 new clinics (Arapahoe, Rock Creek & Wheatridge) came on board in January 2018 but there was a lapse in identifying a clinic champion, due to which the books did not get distributed close to February. 
2. At some clinics, the Pediatrics department receives support from Primary Care physicians to see some of their Pediatrics well-child visits. When the child is seen in Primary Care, the child does not receive a book.

column16: Program lapse due to ADMINISTRATIVE personnel changes
column17:
Many sites ran out of books - for all or selected age groups and did not receive the next shipment until well after January 2019.  We are also assuming that the # of well visits reflects only those visits to pediatrics (and not to family practice).  This is the data which was requested thus assume it accurately reflects solely well visits to pediatricians as family practice at Kaiser at this time is not participating in the program.
It is also possible that record keeping of books handed out was not perfect.

column16: Program lapse due to ADMINISTRATIVE personnel changes
column17:
In addition to the loss of many staff members who were actively involved in ROR and who were tasked with keeping data, I also  am concerned that the # of well visits is over estimated.  When we began to record the actual # of well visits at our office at the local level versus using the data provided by a central Kaiser office, and compared to the # of books handed out, the percentages are much better.
For example at ACP:  In October we handed out 173 books and had 186 well visits -   93%
In November, we handed out 142 books and had 143 well visits - 99%
In December we handed out 153 books and had 150 well visits - 100%

This data is far better than the overall rate of 63% for our site  - Aurora Centerpoint. To those of us working there, this lower number just felt inaccurate.

I am not sure how to account for this discrepancy.  I suspect that the numbers of well visits which I obtain from a central Kaiser office are simply not correct - and perhaps include all visits scheduled - which may to reflect no shows and cancellations.

Going forward, I think we need to ask each site to keep track of the # of well visits; instead of relying on data from a more centralized source.  Also would like to add that since our numbers of well visits do not perhaps represent reality; we would understand if ROR needs to adjust the book budget.

I would also like to point out that the Arapahoe site was only able to provide data from mid September - end of December.

So - in summary we have some work to do to make sure that the # of well visits at the 9 sites is accurately reported.

I think that COVID-19 had a really significant effect on book distribution. Early in the pandemic, we were focusing on seeing children that needed vaccines  and holding off seeing kids that were up to date (ages 2-4). We did well checks, but they may have been virtual (video visit). There was also concern early in COVID about 'easy spread of COVID on fomites,' so some patients were uncomfortable taking books due to infection concern.

column17: Clinical manager resigned, office staff has changed.  Now have consistent nursing staff.  Also have VFC program fully operational which has increased our peds appointments

column3: Custer County Clinic   Custer County Medical Center

column17: Due to staff turnover, our caseload has been down as we try to fill vacancies and enroll clients into their caseload again.

We have been below caseload for our site due to a decline in referrals, and were short one nurse, resulting in fewer eligible children receiving books.  We are working at strengthening our referral stream, and we are now fully-staffed, so we expect to be providing many more books this year!

Due to a leadership transition and several staffing and system changes on our team in 2019, our site did not distribute as many books as we had corresponding "well-visits".  Our team will discuss the ROR program at our March team meeting, and have established several strategies to better maximize ROR book distribution to our eligible families.

We had several reasons for under-distributing this year.  Our nurses are not conducting in-person visits so we are sending books in Client Kits sent at various timepoints.  RNs need to sign their clients up to receive these kits and they have prioritized the earlier kits with fewer of the Infancy, 12 Mo and 18 Mo kits being sent.  Additionally, our on-sight coordinator NHV resigned very suddenly and we have been scrambling a bit to do her job until a new RN rep was identified.  Our business support staff in charge of building and mailing the kits was using the "free books" when we ran low on certain purchased RORCO books, and we did not have a process for keeping track of these books, so our distribution numbers look lower than normal.

On 10 1 2022, the Tri-County NFP site absorbed the caseload previously funded by Centura Health Systems.  Due to client and staff attrition during this transition, Tri-County NFP is not serving the 370 families we are funded to serve.  As we hire staff and build caseload, we expect to be providing a higher number of ROAR books in the next six months.  In addition, Covid-19 restrictions have prevented in-person visits and not all clients have received the full complement of ROAR books despite efforts to mail books to clients during the pandemic.  As the program completes more visits in-person due to the lifting of pandemic restrictions, we anticipate being able to provide ROAR books at the prescribed time points.

We are training lots of new nurses AND we have a tremendous amount of change happening in our program due to our agency's dissolution as of 12 31 22 that doesn't allow for the ideal time needed to promote RORCO and remind nurses of the importance of proving books at the recommended time points, but we're doing better than last year!

Expected to see more clients due to staffing shortage previously and incentive packages with Reach Out and Read books were not being sent consistently by all nurses. Now this process is more consistent and three new nurses will be added to staff, creating more opportunities for book delivery.

RORCO books were given out less systematically this past year through mailed incentive packages to clients during specific time periods. Books were included but not all nurses took advantage of the ability to mail these packages to clients and families. The team hired 4 new nurses during this time period, as well, and their caseloads primarily begin with pregnant clients. This will change in the following time period as they have more opportunities to work with infants. Also, due to funds being distributed throughout the time period instead of in one lump sum, it was difficult to buy enough RORCO books for all ages of infants toddlers seen in the program. The above numbers are based on the potential number of opportunities to give books but can be affected by disengaged clients, client phase in the program, COVID and telehealth vs. in-person visits, and or available books on hand.

RORCO books were given out less systematically this past year through mailed incentive packages to clients during specific time periods. Books were included but not all nurses took advantage of the ability to mail these packages to clients and families. As nurses began to return to in-person visits, the books were included in incentive packages and the mailing service was discontinued. As nurses increased their in-person visits and began to distribute more RORCO books, the variant arrived and many visits were again converted to telehealth, except now without the option of mailing books to clients. Lastly, the team expanded by 4 new nurses in October and they required orientation to the TCHD process of distributing RORCO books. This will continue to change in the following time period as more nurses return to in-person visitation, the expanded team consistently delivers books and even more nurses are hired. The above numbers are based on the potential number of opportunities to give books but can be affected by disengaged clients, client phase in the program, COVID and telehealth vs. in-person visits, and or available books on hand.
